  "issue_title": "[BUG] CLI commands return exit code 0 on runtime/import failures",
  "issue_body": "## Description\n\nSeveral CLI commands print an error when a runtime/import failure happens, but still exit with code `0`.\nThis makes automation/CI treat failed commands as success.\n\nAffected command groups include:\n- `gitt admin ...`\n- `gitt vote ...`\n- `gitt issues register`\n- `gitt harvest`\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\n\n1. Trigger a runtime/import failure in one of the commands above (example: run `gitt harvest` in an environment missing required runtime deps, or with a patched failing client init).\n2. Observe that the CLI prints an error message (for example, `Missing dependency ...` or a runtime exception message).\n3. Check exit code with `echo $?` and see it is `0`.\n\n## Expected Behavior\n\nCLI should exit with a non-zero status code when command execution fails due to runtime/import exceptions.\n\n## Actual Behavior\n\nCLI prints the error but exits with code `0`, causing false-positive success in scripts/CI.\n\n## Environment\n\n- OS: Ubuntu (please fill exact version)\n- Python version: 3.12 (please fill exact patch version)\n- Commit/Version: `test` branch (please fill exact commit hash)\n\n## Additional Context\n\nThis is especially problematic for automation pipelines and shell scripts that rely on exit codes for failure detection.\n",
